{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471808"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:51:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"872"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/872"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.04,0.45,0.36,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105152"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/872"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87572"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"563"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17831"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17855"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105152"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 7-year-old girl is brought into a general practice clinic by her concerned mother because she is being teased at school because of her height. Her mother says that her daughter appears \u0027shorter than all her friends\u0027.  Her maternal and child health record book up to age four showed a height on the 2nd percentile and weight on the 10th percentile, never crossing two percentile lines. She is an otherwise well child with no medical conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial examination or measurement to perform?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bone age","Tanner staging","Plot height, weight, and growth velocity","Plotting mid-parental height","Skin fold thickness"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child would be described as having short stature, defined as a length or height below the 3rd percentile (\u0026gt;2 standard deviations from the mean). Short stature is not always pathological, but it is important to assess for any underlying causes. Red flags for pathological growth failure include crossing of two major percentile lines for height or height velocity below the 25th percentile, hence these should be replotted as her last measurements were not completed recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial step in evaluating a child with short stature is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eplot height, weight, and growth velocity\u003C/strong\u003E. Her height, weight and growth velocity today to identify if she is still in the same percentile lines as documented at age 4 years.  This allows for the assessment of the child\u0027s growth pattern over time and helps identify any deviations from expected growth trajectories. Consistent growth along a low percentile without crossing two major percentile lines may suggest a non-pathological cause, such as familial short stature or constitutional growth delay. This step is crucial as it provides a baseline for further investigations if needed. For this patient, her height and weight had been tracked during the maternal health nurse consultations which ends at age 4, \u003Cstrong\u003Ethus the last 3 years of her growth data is not charted.\u003C/strong\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone age\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful tool for assessing growth potential and diagnosing conditions like constitutional growth delay or endocrine disorders. However, it is not the first step in the evaluation process. It is typically used after initial growth assessments indicate a potential problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETanner staging\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assess pubertal development. In a 7-year-old, this is less relevant unless there are signs of precocious puberty, which is not the case here. Precocious puberty usually results in tall stature initially due to the pubertal growth spurt.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlotting mid-parental height\u003C/strong\u003E can provide insight into genetic potential for growth, but it is secondary to assessing actual growth patterns and velocity. While it helps determine if the child\u0027s growth is consistent with familial patterns, it does not provide immediate information about the child\u0027s current growth trajectory or potential underlying issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin fold thickness\u003C/strong\u003E is a measure of body fat and is not directly relevant to the assessment of short stature. It is more applicable in nutritional assessments or evaluating obesity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Short stature is defined as a length or height below the 3rd percentile (\u003E2 standard deviations from the mean).","Plotting height, weight, and growth velocity is crucial in assessing growth patterns and identifying deviations from expected trajectories.","Mid-parental height is useful for assessing genetic potential but is secondary to evaluating actual growth patterns."],"references":["Cohen P, Rogol AD, Deal CL, et al. Consensus statement on the diagnosis and treatment of children with idiopathic short stature: a summary of the Growth Hormone Research Society, the Lawson Wilkins Pediatric Endocrine Society, and the European Society for Paediatric Endocrinology Workshop. J Clin Endocrinol Metab 2008; 93:4210.","Simm PJ, Werther GA. Child and adolescent growth disorders--an overview. Aust Fam Physician. 2005 Sep;34(9):731-7. PMID: 16184204.","Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Growth charts. Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. n.d. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/childgrowth/about_child_growth/Growth_charts/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87572"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"872"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87572"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-08T00:12:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-08T00:12:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"872"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105152"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"ty